title: Vast Agricultural Land Coverage
description: In 2022, 84.55% of Turkmenistan's land area was dedicated to agriculture, highlighting its significant agricultural potential.

title: High Fossil Fuel Dependency
description: As of 2022, Turkmenistan's energy consumption was entirely reliant on fossil fuels, accounting for 100% of its total energy use.

title: Universal Prenatal Care Coverage
description: In 2019, 100% of pregnant women in Turkmenistan received prenatal care, ensuring comprehensive maternal health services.

title: High Out-of-Pocket Health Expenditure
description: In 2022, 79.22% of Turkmenistan's current health expenditure was out-of-pocket, indicating a significant financial burden on individuals.

title: Strong Female Labor Force Participation
description: By 2024, the ratio of female to male labor force participation in Turkmenistan was 104.66%, showcasing gender parity in employment.

title: Minimal Open Defecation in Rural Areas
description: In 2018, only 0.0026% of the rural population in Turkmenistan practiced open defecation, reflecting effective sanitation measures.

title: Low Renewable Energy Output
description: In 2021, renewable energy accounted for a mere 0.01% of Turkmenistan's total electricity output, indicating a need for diversification.

title: High Domestic Private Health Expenditure
description: In 2022, 84.50% of Turkmenistan's health expenditure was funded privately, highlighting the role of private sector in healthcare.

title: High Consumption of Iodized Salt
description: In 2015, 99.7% of households in Turkmenistan consumed iodized salt, ensuring adequate iodine nutrition across the population.

title: Limited Control of Corruption
description: In 2022, Turkmenistan ranked low in control of corruption with a percentile rank of 0.47, indicating governance challenges.

title: Low Voice and Accountability
description: In 2023, Turkmenistan's voice and accountability percentile rank was 0.49, reflecting limited political freedoms and civic participation.

title: Minimal Female Adolescents Out of School
description: In 2022, only 0.02% of female adolescents were out of school in Turkmenistan, indicating high educational retention rates.

title: Significant Merchandise Imports from Europe & Central Asia
description: In 2023, 45.24% of Turkmenistan's merchandise imports were from low- and middle-income economies in Europe & Central Asia.

title: Low Statistical Performance in Data Services
description: In 2023, Turkmenistan scored 0.47 in statistical performance indicators for data services, suggesting room for improvement in data management.

title: Negative Aid Flows from Norway
description: In 2019, Turkmenistan experienced negative net bilateral aid flows from Norway, amounting to -$20,000, indicating a financial outflow.

title: Positive Official Flows from UN IAEA
description: In 2022, Turkmenistan received $13,054 in net official flows from UN IAEA, supporting its nuclear energy initiatives.
